SUMMARY: Story Tellers
DESCRIPTION:Northshore Concert Band presents Story Tellers: A Musical Jou
 rney Through Childhood and Imagination\n\nThis April\, the Northshore Con
 cert Band invites audiences to rediscover the wonder of childhood with St
 ory Tellers\, an imaginative concert program celebrating curiosity\, adve
 nture\, and the magic of storytelling through music.\n\nThe program opens
  with Adam Schoenberg’s Rise\, a powerful and uplifting work that reflect
 s both hopeful beginnings and heartfelt farewells. With its vibrant orche
 stration and emotional depth\, Rise feels less like a story being told an
 d more like a life moment being shared. It sets the stage for an afternoo
 n that explores the innocence\, joy\, and discovery of youth.\n\nPercy Gr
 ainger’s Children’s March follows\, brings youthful exuberance to life wi
 th lilting melodies and boundless energy. Considered a cornerstone of win
 d band repertoire\, it carries listeners “over the hills and far away.” T
 he spirit of adventure continues with selections from Joe Hisaishi’s belo
 ved score to the animated film My Neighbor Totoro. Through vivid musical 
 scenes\, the audience encounters the cuddly Totoro\, the whimsical Catbus
 \, and the charming escapades of sisters Satsuki and Mei.\n\nThe concert 
 journeys into the enchanting world of Hans Christian Andersen with Martin
  Ellerby’s Tales from Andersen. This imaginative suite transforms classic
  fairy tales into colorful musical vignettes\, including The Emperor’s Ne
 w Clothes and The Snow Queen—the timeless story that inspired Disney’s an
 imated film Frozen.\n\nThe program concludes with selections from John Wi
 lliams’ sweeping score to Far and Away. Blending Irish folk influences wi
 th the expansive spirit of the American West\, the music propels a hopefu
 l journey toward new beginnings.\n\nThrough beloved stories\, evocative m
 elodies\, and vibrant orchestration\, Story Tellers invites audiences of 
 all ages to see the world through the eyes of a child—full of wonder\, im
 agination\, and possibility.\n\nJoin us this April for Story Tellers and 
 experience an unforgettable musical celebration of childhood\, discovery\
 , and the timeless power of storytelling.\n\nAdam Schoenberg - Rise\n\nPe
 rcy Grainger - Children’s March\n\nJoe Hisaishi (arr. Goto) - My Neighbor
  Totoro\n\nMartin Ellerby - Tales from Andersen\n\nJohn Williams (arr. La
 vender) - Far and Away\n\nTickets are priced at $25 for adults\, $20 for 
 seniors\, and $10 for students/children. All seats are general admission.
  Group discounts are available for parties of 10 or more. Please visit ht
 tp://northshoreband.org to purchase tickets online through Eventbrite.\n\
 nStory Tellers\n\nApril 12\, 2026 | 3:00 pm\n\nPick-Staiger Concert Hall\
 n\nNorthwestern University\n\nEvanston\, IL\n\nAbout the Northshore Conce
 rt Band\nThe Northshore Concert Band\, now in its 70th year\, is a premie
 r community wind ensemble based in the Chicago area. Dedicated to artisti
 c excellence\, community engagement\, and music education\, the ensemble 
 performs a diverse repertoire ranging from traditional wind band classics
  to contemporary works and beloved film scores\, offering audiences inspi
 ring musical experiences throughout the year.
CATEGORIES:Arts,Family-Friendly
